<DOC><DOCNO> AP880604-0042 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-88 0432EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     06-04 0278</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Political Briefs,270</SECOND><HEAD>Democrats Say GOP Vulnerable on Family Issues</HEAD><DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The head of the Democratic party'splatform committee says the party can regain the White House byfocusing on issues affecting U.S. families and developing proposalsthat are affordable.   ``We are picking this issue because we felt it is a new frontierfor America. We have a good record of family issues,'' saidMichigan Gov. James Blanchard Friday at an issues forum.   ``The Republicans have spent the last eight years trying toregulate our bedrooms and tell us what prayers to pray,'' addedBlanchard, who heads the 163-member panel that will prepare aplatform for the Democratic National Convention in July.   Blanchard said Republicans had gutted programs affectinglow-income families, the young and the elderly, and Americans see aneed for such programs. But he cautioned, Democrats must convincevoters such initiatives are financially feasible.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Bush Campaign `Preferred Delegates Lists' Irritates Colorado GOP</HEAD><DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Some state Republicans are angry because VicePresident George Bush's Colorado campaign is pushing so-called``preferred delegates lists'' as state delegates to the RepublicanNational Convention.   The handpicked choices being supported by the Bush campaign aremade up mostly of his campaign workers.   Bush's son, Neil of Denver, has been campaigning for the slatesand said the move is not divisive.   ``We're doing it for party unity sake, because we've included inour statewide delegate list for tomorrow people from (New York Rep.Jack) Kemp and (Kansas Sen. Bob) Dole,'' he said Friday.   Eighteen delegates have been picked and the remaining 18 are tobe selected today at the party's state convention at McNicholsSports Arena.</TEXT>